</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ulasorcier.showPublicProfile?language=EN>LaSorcier</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/18/02 7:45:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1057.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> Actually, on the estate tax side of the issue, you can have an estate as small as $1 million and still be subject to estate tax.  Although, if your estate is less than $2 million and you're paying estate taxes, you didn't plan very well.  <br>
<br>
If you think these are large amounts that only a select few can ever realize from life, here is some interesting information.<br>
<br>
Assuming at age 30 you were to contribute the maximum 2001 amount of $10,500 to your 401(k) plan until age 65; you would have an asset of $1,977,927 assuming a growth rate of 10%.  Even with a rate of growth as low as 7%, you are exceeding $1m in value.  <br>
<br>
The bottom line is that if you aren't putting anything at all in your employer's 401(k) plan, you need to seriously rethink that strategy.<br>
<br>
Note that this doesn't even include your employer's contribution.  The bottom line is that a 401(k) is the absolute easiest way to have a nice retirement income stream.  Sure, it may bite in the early years when your cash needs are higher due to student loans and such, but it is a worthwhile sacrifice.  <br>
<br>
On the interest-free loan line, when you owe the government, you aren't necessarily receiving an interest-free loan from it.  It will hit you with a penalty that is computed as interest, if you did not estimate your taxes properly.  <br>
